Every Sunday morning my son runs out for Starbucks coffee and breakfast.&nbsp;&nbsp; I don't know if it can be called a tradition since it started less than a year ago, but it is certainly a regularly scheduled event.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mike drives whichever car is lowest on fuel and stops by the gas station to fill it up.&nbsp;&nbsp; The food and drink order is virtually the same every week, but still we have to write it down or we risk getting something completely different.&nbsp;&nbsp; Lately I have been trying to change my order towards something a little more healthy, although Burger King Cheesy Tots don't qualify as health food.&nbsp;&nbsp; Small steps I suppose.

Yesterday morning, Mike was startled when he opened the door to leave for the Sunday breakfast run.&nbsp;&nbsp; A small gray striped cat was waiting at the door.&nbsp; Mike stopped and looked at the cat, the cat looked back and with a little mewl walked in as if he owned the place.&nbsp;&nbsp; 

"Who are you?" Mike asked.&nbsp;&nbsp; Mike was actually smiling when he spoke to the cat.&nbsp;&nbsp; I think he actually expected an answer.

"Mew, Meeeew, MEW!" the cat cried.&nbsp; &nbsp; The lithe body crouched low to the carpet as he reached the middle of the room. &nbsp; Tuxedo had just appeared at the kitchen door, his tail three times thicker than normal, his ears pinned back. &nbsp;&nbsp; 

The gray cat turned and looked at me. &nbsp; I stared back. &nbsp; Just as I started to move the visitor jumped into my lap and rubbed his cheek against my hand. &nbsp; I was startled at how cold his fur was against my hand.&nbsp; As I stroked his back I realized that the cold went deeper than the fur, his skin was like ice. &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;  

I pulled the cat closer to my chest and tried to warm him while keeping a close watch on the location of his paws.&nbsp; So far he seemed friendly but I wasn't taking any chances.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As I rubbed his head I tried to turn the collar to read the gold circular tag that dangled there.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The tag was the size of a dime and the writing was too small for me to read easily.&nbsp;&nbsp; My glasses weren't close enough to grab and the writing was so very tiny.&nbsp;&nbsp; It still surprises me at how many different things make me feel old.

I was finally able to read the phone number and at the same time learned that our visitor's name was Bandit.&nbsp;&nbsp; Mike grabbed Tuxedo and took him downstairs as Carol called Bandit's family.&nbsp;&nbsp; Bandit had started getting anxious and his hind claws were starting to poke through the denim of my jeans.&nbsp;&nbsp; He started to calm down as soon as Tuxedo was out of sight, and he settled into my chest and reached up to rub his cheek against my face.&nbsp;&nbsp; 

Bandit was well fed and seemed more interested in warming himself than anything else.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Holding the cat and keeping him from exploring the house seemed to be the wisest course of action.&nbsp; Meanwhile Carol copied the address down and explained to Bandit's family that we weren't interested in any reward.

Mike set the cat carrier, pulled from the closet, onto the couch and opened the door.&nbsp;&nbsp; I cradled Bandit in my arms, stood and walked over to the carrier.&nbsp;&nbsp; The sounds that Bandit made as I tried to put him into the small plastic cage were nothing short of startling.&nbsp;&nbsp; They were the most un-cat like squeaks and groans that I had ever heard.&nbsp;&nbsp; Squirming and squeaking, writhing and hissing, yet all the while a deep purr emanated from deep within the gray short haired feline.&nbsp; 

When I was able to close and latch the door Bandit turned and looked out at me and with a quiet but firm "Mew" he let me know that he was ready to go.&nbsp;&nbsp; Maybe he mean to say that he was unhappy with me for putting him the cold unhappy place.&nbsp; I prefer to think the former.

After Mike left the house, carrier and Bandit in hand, I walked downstairs and released Tuxedo from the bathroom prison he endured with such dignity.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tuxedo lifted his chin and his tail high into the air and exited the bathroom with an affected air of royalty.&nbsp;&nbsp; He climbed the stairs deliberately and without the slightest betrayal of any fear of the intruder.&nbsp;&nbsp; He sniffed around the upstairs and then inspected his food area and after assuring himself that he was again the reigning king of the land he returned to his normal resting place and lay down for a nap.

Mike refused the reward money for returning Bandit to his home.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I don't know if we will see Bandit again, or if he will stay closer to home.&nbsp;&nbsp; If he does wander off again I hope he is just as polite to the next family he visits.

After five hours of cleaning the house is finally at a point where I won't be embarrassed to have a delivery person look inside the front door.  The major piles of crap have been redistributed to more appropriate locations.  Dishes that were used almost a week ago have finally been washed and put away.  The dining room table can actually be used to serve a meal, after another pass of disinfectant cleaner.   I can walk from the front door to the kitchen without having to weave left or right around dirty clothes, shopping bags, or empty boxes.   I can sit in my chair and look around without feeling sick to my stomach.   It has been a productive day.

The house is far from clean. &nbsp; The surface has been scratched and&nbsp; although slight, the progress feels good. &nbsp;&nbsp; I can't describe the level of anxiety reached earlier today. &nbsp; The family finally left on the vacation trip around noon, leaving me alone to get some work done for the office.&nbsp; I tried to sit and focus on the computer screen and the level of mess around me filled my vision. &nbsp; I couldn't sit still while surrounded by so much mess. &nbsp; 

To be honest&nbsp; it is all just clutter and about four days worth of dirty dishes and a kitchen floor that needs a serious amount of sweeping and a hot mop.&nbsp; Well, then there are several baskets worth of clothing strewn about the master bedroom, bathrooms that need to be hosed down, and cat boxes that hadn't been changed in waaaay too long.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 

I focused on things that smelled, and things I could see when trying to work.&nbsp;&nbsp; The cat boxes have been changed, the dishes are done, and the main floor clutter has been excised.&nbsp;&nbsp; Now I can sit down and work without my heart beating in my throat and blood rushing in my ears.&nbsp;&nbsp; The anxiety reached a level that nearly brought tears to my eyes.

I wish I could ignore the other people in the house and just keep it clean.&nbsp; When I am not alone I feel as though I shouldn't be the only one... I shouldn't have to do all the work myself... I try to keep things clean and organized, and then something in me just gives up...&nbsp; I just stop trying to do it all and nothing gets done.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I rationalize my behavior, telling myself that I am just waiting until someone else pitches in or that I shouldn't bother if no-one else cares.&nbsp;&nbsp; 

In the end though it affects my entire day.&nbsp; When the house is a mess my self esteem drops and I start to doubt everything about myself.&nbsp;&nbsp; When I feel bad I convince myself that I am not worth taking care of and my diet goes out the window.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Now I am making it sound like all of my problems stem from living in a dirty house.&nbsp; Not true... I have lots of problems, this is just the one that I am complaining about today.

My family is away for three days.&nbsp;&nbsp; I get the house to myself.&nbsp;&nbsp; Right now I wish it were for a month, I wonder how I will feel in a few days.

I am feeling very depressed today. &nbsp; It started at the Renaissance Festival.&nbsp; I was at the House of Musical Traditions looking at hand drums.&nbsp; I want to pick up an inexpensive djembe, bongo drums, or similar small hand drum. &nbsp; I want to learn to play some basic rhythms so I can appreciate the cajone that Jay has offered to make.&nbsp;&nbsp; But as I looked and was offered to try them I couldn't bring myself to even try. I felt incapable of playing or even trying in front of people.&nbsp; 

The same thing happened to me when I was looking at the cajone while Jay looked on.&nbsp; I couldn't bring myself to even try.&nbsp;&nbsp; I was embarrassed and felt insignificant in front of those around me.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When Doug let me try his PRS guitar I had the same reaction.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It is the same thing that is keeping me from taking my bass guitar to jam with Doug and Jay.

Now I am sitting here and the anxiety is filling my chest and I feel more foolish than ever.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
